{"id":"astro-ph/0602060","submitter":"Pawan Kumar","authors":"P. Kumar, E. McMahon, S. D. Barthelmy, D. Burrows, N. Gehrels, M.\n  Goad, J. Nousek, and G. Tagliaferri","title":"A unified picture for gamma-ray burst prompt and X-ray afterglow\n  emissions","comments":"5 pages 3 figures. to appear in MNRAS letter","journal-ref":"Mon.Not.Roy.Astron.Soc.Lett.367:L52-L56,2006","doi":"10.1111/j.1745-3933.2006.00138.x","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Data from the Swift satellite has enabled us for the first time to provide a\ncomplete picture of the gamma-ray burst emission mechanism and its relationship\nwith the early afterglow emissions. We show that gamma-ray photons for two\nbursts, 050126 & 050219A, for which we have carried out detailed analysis were\nproduced as a result of the synchrotron self-Compton process in the material\nejected in the explosion when it was heated to a mildly relativistic\ntemperature at a distance from the center of explosion of order the\ndeceleration radius. Both of these bursts exhibit rapidly declining early X-ray\nafterglow lightcurves; this emission is from the same source that produced the\ngamma-ray burst. The technique we exploit to determine this is very general and\nmakes no assumption about any particular model for gamma-ray generation except\nthat the basic radiation mechanism is some combination of synchrotron and\ninverse-Compton processes in a relativistic outflow. For GRB 050219A we can\nrule out the possibility that energy from the explosion is carried outward by\nmagnetic fields, and that the dissipation of this field produced the\n$\\gamma$-ray burst.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 2 Feb 2006 23:55:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2010-03-19"}
